author: 4ef8ca9e-4865-5cbb-be66-9b82d18f07bd
content:
There are huge caveats with a recommendation of this game.

The gameplay when everything comes together is incredible. The feeling of clutching a round for your team, especially when you're with friends, is beaten only by the elation of winning a close-fought match through sheer doggedness and team spirit. Frankly, in those kinds of matches even losing 16-14 can leave you with a smile on your face.

However, I don't know how I would get into this game as a beginner nowadays. Though if I didn't know better I'd probably try the free-to-play version, I recommend at least paying for a Prime-enabled account. The problem with cheaters is very large and could lead to a quick disillusionment with the game. Some veterans even leave the game because of this problem. It's such a terrible sinking feeling when you arrive in a match and see an enemy, or even a teammate, spinbotting or obviously hacking. You just know you've wasted the next 15 minutes or, if they only start hacking after they get angry and falsely believe you're hacking, you've wasted even longer. Either that or you can leave, but you will get a cooldown from matchmaking servers for abandoning a match! 

If you are intent on learning it competitively, I'd suggest researching third-party services like faceit (available for anyone as far as I know) or ECL (I believe currently only hosting servers located in Europe). ECL actively moderates its users and seems to have a fairly welcoming community, perhaps it would be relatively easy to find people of a similar skill level willing to help out a beginner. Unfortunately I think the base experience in Valve's own matchmaking system can be horrible and beginners might have a decent experience, or a completely off-putting one with toxic teammates who can't remember what it was like to be new in the game.

Prepare for the worst. I hope you get to enjoy the best of what CS has to offer.

author: d7d4a172-f0a4-5828-91fb-da4de6afc9b5
content: I am a 45 yo gamer father, probably one of the oldest gamers playing this game. I am a single gamer father to my Son, who is 14 now. My son got this game for Christmas in 2021 from his gamer uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 24 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. So i decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe destroy him repeatedly in 1v1s to ruin his new hobby for him. I loaded into the game, picked my character and world and started playing but I was stuck on what you were supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he hosted a game for me to join. I won every game, and spent the whole evening pulling off mad trick shots with the AWP and sending racial slurs in the chat until he uninstalled the game. I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my non-gamer wife had died. This game has ever since been the source of a rift between me and my son, and I never let him play on my team because he’s an absolute bot. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought me many happy memories.

author: af39987c-f161-5b02-ab13-7141efe52eb4
content:
One of the best FPS games in the world. It is fun, competitive and sometimes stressful (bad teammates or cheaters). Sometimes I feel glad I am still playing the game, sometimes I question myself why do I keep playing this game plagued with cheaters. Basically, the game is fun but when you come across a cheater or troll/griefer/toxic people, it becomes a nightmare you wanna get the heck out of real FAST.

For new players out there don't jump into comp right away, try all the modes, watch youtube videos, watch past PRO league tournaments, watch some popular/high rank twitch streamers, learn the maps, the callouts, the jargons, the line ups, common angles, and just have fun. Sometimes you win, sometimes you lose. It is what it is. I highly recommend the short competitive mode when you are finally ready to do some Competitive matches. Good luck, have fun!

author: fb28d22a-5f87-579b-80c7-d6d7875baa3c
content:
The action remains, as ever, beautifully balanced but brutally difficult. While awards are doled out for kills in the form of achievements and cash rewards, there are no perks or kill streaks and no persistent advantages to levelling up. If you haven’t played for a while you’ll find yourself getting trashed by players who know the tricks and the maps better than you, and it takes a certain level of persistence not to give up and crawl back to the Battlefield or Modern Warfare threequels. Valve has implemented a new matchmaking system, designed to fit you with players of your own skill level, but while this gives you a fighting chance it doesn’t remove the steep difficulty curve entirely. You will get better, but it’s going to take some time, some practice, and some experience against other players.

Luckily, Global Offensive is replete with ways to get all three. First, you can practice against bots, using the time to get a feel for the controls and learn the maps, the choke-points and the sneaky routes to hostages and bomb sites without the humiliation of fighting against someone who’s happy to inform you how badly you suck.
